<HEADLINE>
FT  24 NOV 94 / International Company News: Videotron falls despite 10%
sales increase
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Expanding cable-TV operations in Canada and the UK enabled Videotron to
report a 10 per cent rise in revenues for the year ended August 31, but
higher depreciation and continuing problems in domestic broadcasting
depressed profits overall.
Net profit was CDollars 20.5m (USDollars 14.6m), or 11 cents a share, down
from CDollars 25.1m, or 15 cents a share, a year earlier on revenues of
CDollars 641m against CDollars 584m.
Videotron has been investing heavily in its cable and telecommunications
franchise areas in southern England, leading to higher depreciation and
amortisation.
However, Videotron said the UK unit would contribute more in 1995 and
eventually be a significant source of income and cash flow.
Videotron will also start up a trial commercial cable/multi-media system in
Quebec this autumn and is expanding rapidly in the US. Newbridge Networks, a
specialised telecommunication equipment maker, posted a second-quarter
profit of CDollars 45.3m, or 56 cents a share, on sales of CDollars 191m, up
almost 50 per cent. First-half profit was CDollars 87.2m, or CDollars 1.08 a
share, up from CDollars 69.1m, or 87 cents, on sales of CDollars 363m
against CDollars 243m.
