<HEADLINE>
FT  24 NOV 94 / International Company News: Metallgesellschaft plans call
for further DM600m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A capital restructuring package, including a call on shareholders for a
further DM600m (Dollars 387m) and a two-to-one capital reduction, is being
prepared for presentation at Metallgesellschaft's annual meeting next March.
Describing the scheme as 'only a concept', Mr Kajo Neukirchen, chairman of
the battered German metals and engineering group, said yesterday the aim
would be to offer shares in the capital increase at a substantial discount
to the market rate.
Shares in this year's DM1.4bn rights issue, part of a DM3.4bn rescue
arranged by bank shareholders, were priced well above the market at DM250.
The stock was suspended yesterday pending the announcement, after closing at
DM143 on Tuesday.
Despite the lack of detail, the fact that plans for a capital write-down
have been announced suggests German creditor banks, which tightly control
the company, have already agreed in principle.
A restructuring of the group's capital base has long been expected. It is
viewed as the logical consequence of the operational shake-out which has led
to the sale and closure of many subsidiaries.
The assets sale instituted last December has generated more than DM4bn, and
90 subsidiaries have been disposed of or deconsolidated.
Mr Neukirchen said yesterday the sell-off was virtually complete, apart from
the planned disposal of the Lentjes plant and pipeline activities.
He repeated earlier forecasts of operating earnings exceeding DM100m in the
year to the end of September 1995.
Mr Neukirchen also expanded on 1993-94 figures published last week which
showed a net loss of DM2.7bn on sales of DM20bn, compared with a with a
deficit of DM1.97bn on DM26bn turnover.
Trading and services divisions earned DM38m pre-tax on sales up DM1bn at
DM8.7bn, after losing DM33m last time. Plant construction under the Lurgi
group fell into a loss of DM35m, but only after setting aside DM110m for
redundancies and early retirements.
Dynamit Nobel has bought two more chemical concerns from its parent company
Metallgesellschaft, concentrating all of the latter's chemicals activities
under one roof, Reuter adds.
The two subsidiaries Dynamit Nobel purchased are Sachtleben Chemie of
Duisburg-Homberg, and the Chemson Group, with factories in Austria and the
UK.
