<HEADLINE>
FT  24 NOV 94 / Granada focuses on expansion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Granada group is considering expansion in continental Europe through
acquisitions in catering and services.
The new focus was revealed yesterday as the television, leisure and services
group announced a record pre-tax profit of Pounds 265m for the 52 weeks to
October 1 - a rise of 51 per cent.
Granada, following the failure of its attempts to acquire Gardner Merchant,
the catering group, is faced with the prospect of increasing profits and a
debt-free business within three years if it makes no new significant
acquisitions.
Mr Gerry Robinson, chief executive, said: 'We might look at European
motorways, European catering businesses and public catering.'
The group, one of the largest ITV companies owning Granada Television and
London Weekend Television, can add little to its UK television interests
without a change in regulations.
Mr Robinson said: 'The most likely outcome is that we don't have
acquisitions over the next 18 months. I would like that not to be true but
it will only not be true if we find the right thing.' He conceded the
company might have to return more money to shareholders if the right deals
do not come along.
Yesterday Granada reported strong growth both in its existing businesses and
in the year's two most recent large acquisitions - Sutcliffe Catering and
LWT.
Mr Robinson was bullish about the future. He said the company looked forward
to 1995 with confidence 'in our ability to improve margins and with
expectation that our own capacity to generate organic growth from our
principal businesses will be enhanced by an improving economy'.
Turnover rose 30 per cent to Pounds 2.09bn and operating profit grew by 46
per cent to Pounds 299m. Fully diluted earnings per share rose29 per cent to
32p. The dividend was lifted 14 per cent to 10p.
If the British Sky Broadcasting flotation goes ahead at the mid-price
Granada will get rid of around Pounds 120m in contingency liabilities plus a
total of around Pounds 40m in cash.
Some analysts are now looking for around Pounds 317m in profit in the
current financial year.
Yesterday Granada shares closed unchanged at 516p, after touching a high of
524p earlier in the day.
