<HEADLINE>
FT  24 NOV 94 / Maxwell lawyers say media made fair trial impossible
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Defence lawyers are seeking to have the Maxwell brothers' trial on fraud and
other charges called off on the grounds that publicity over the Maxwell
affair has made a fair trial impossible.
The attempt to halt the criminal proceedings against Kevin and Ian Maxwell
was disclosed in court for the first time yesterday when the Serious Fraud
Office applied for a reporting ban on a current High Court case concerning
Maxwell pension fund assets used to raise a Pounds 50m loan.
A successful SFO application would rule out any reporting of the attempt by
UK pensioners to recover Pounds 60m from Credit Suisse bank, which accepted
the assets as collateral for the loan. The SFO said the ban was necessary to
avoid prejudicing the trials, to start after Easter next year.
The Credit Suisse case is expected to end next summer, but if the SFO
succeeds, pensioners could be left in ignorance of the result for a further
two years, their lawyers argued.
Mr Justice Lindsay, the Credit Suisse case judge, rejected an SFO request
for reporting restrictions on yesterday's hearing.
Arguments over calling off the criminal proceedings against all defendants
in the Maxwell fraud trial will be heard in January.
First in line for trial will be four of the six facing various fraud charges
 -Kevin and Ian Maxwell, Mr Larry Trachtenberg, former adviser to Mr Robert
Maxwell, and Mr Robert Bunn, former finance director of Maxwell
Communication Corporation.
In the first trial, Kevin Maxwell will face two charges of a total nine
alleging conspiracy to defraud over pension fund assets. Ian Maxwell, Mr
Trachtenberg and Mr Bunn will face one charge of conspiracy to defraud.
Further proceedings against the four and two former Robert Maxwell
employees, Mr Michael Stoney, a former Mirror Group Newspapers finance
director, and Mr Albert Fuller, a former MGN treasurer, are set to follow.
Mr Michael Crystal QC, for the Mirror Group Pension Fund Trustees, argued
against a blanket reporting ban on the Credit Suisse proceedings. He said
the proceedings might last until 1997 and the order could prevent pensioners
being informed of the result of their action, he said.
The trustees and the liquidators of Bishopsgate Investment Management, the
main Maxwell pension management company, are suing Credit Suisse.
Ten national newspapers are opposing the SFO application. The hearing was
adjourned until December 5.
</TEXT>
