<HEADLINE>
FT  24 NOV 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN HOYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Arousing pity comes easily to television's intimate immediacy. Tonight's
Witness: Life after Death (9pm C4) is one of those gentle, almost deadpan
probings of tragedy that leave you pondering the issues long afterwards. The
scene is Ulster: the Catholic woman whose husband was mistakenly killed by
the IRA is embittered; the ex-Loyalist paramilitary who served a jail
sentence after killing a catholic stranger is almost serene as he
acknowledges his guilt, a born-again Christian. The ways of God and men are
incomprehensible.
The film's integrity contrasts with the perceptible layer of smugness in
Forbidden Britain (9.45 pm BBC2). The series' assumption that we think
society's ills date only from modern times overlooks the fact some of us
read books. The slightly accusing note with which tonight's programme
unearths fascinating film of homelessness is a good fault at a time when the
chattering (and TV-making) classes think of history as a month-old colour
supplement, and are themselves unaware of life before the sixties when not
only sex but civilisation began.
</TEXT>
