<HEADLINE>
FT  24 NOV 94 / Steady recovery for two years predicted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT, Economics Staff and MOTOKO RICH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The economy is improving in an 'uncharacteristically smooth manner', with
steady recovery predicted for at least two more years, according to the
latest quarterly forecast from the National Institute of Economic and Social
Research.
Nevertheless, the private research group questions whether this means that
the UK has achieved any real economic miracle. It suggests that the healthy
combination of low inflation and fast growth simply represents 'the response
that might be expected' in a recovery in an economy that has just
experienced a 'deep recession where balance sheet difficulties were
prevalent'.
Overall, the institute has now revised its forecast for output growth for
1994 up to slightly over 3.5 per cent. This is higher than its forecast of
2.9 per cent growth made in the early summer, but still below most City
forecasts.
Nevertheless, Mr Garry Young, UK economist at the institute, yesterday
pointed out that the forecast had been made before the publication of
official figures last week which showed that gross domestic product in the
third quarter of this year grew at an annual rate of 4.2 per cent. He added
that the forecast would probably be revised further upwards.
Growth for next year is expected to fall to 2.75 per cent, due to a presumed
slowdown in the North Sea oil and gas sector. The institute's underlying
inflation forecast has been revised down, and is now 2.8 per cent for next
year compared with its previous forecast of 3.8 per cent. The institute
notes the main reason for this was low growth in labour costs.
Although the institute does not expect interest rates to rise to the levels
assumed by the markets, it nevertheless predicts that the authorities' tight
anti-inflation stance will help the exchange rate profile to stay broadly
constant. This is in contrast to its previous forecast, which assumed that
sterling would steadily depreciate. Vocational guidance for British school
leavers is inferior to careers advice given to young people in other
European countries, a study released today says, Motoko Rich writes.
The report by the National Institute of Economic and Social Research
compares careers education in the UK with Germany, Switzerland and the
Netherlands.
It found that careers training in mainland Europe gave young people of
'average and below-average attainments' better expectations than in Britain.
The report said that teachers were instructed in vocational guidance while
their British counterparts were not.
Advice was focused on specific careers and continental students were
provided with more effective work experience programmes than young people in
Britain.
National Institute Economic Review, November 1994. NIESR, Dean Trench
Street, Smith Square, London, SW1P 3HE. Annual subscription Pounds 80,
single issue Pounds 25.
</TEXT>
