<HEADLINE>
FT  24 NOV 94 / Societies neutral on regulation shift
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The prospect of bringing building societies within the same regulatory
regime as banks was highlighted yesterday by MPs on the Treasury committee.
The Building Societies Association was asked about the idea of merging the
Building Societies Commission, the sector's statutory regulator, with the
supervisory division of the Bank of England.
It was giving evidence to the committee's inquiry into financial regulation.
Mr Donald Kirkham, association chairman, told the MPs: 'We are fairly
neutral about who regulates us, provided that it's effective.'
While the association said it did not see the need for change and that the
commission had been a successful regulator, Mr Adrian Coles,
director-general, said 'it would not be a dreadful disaster if it was
merged' provided the supervisor's expertise was not lost.
The comments came the day after Nationwide Building Society, the UK's second
largest, called for a single regulatory framework for financial services
with one watchdog covering areas currently handled by a range of
organisations.
Until recently, the arguments for regulatory convergence came largely from
banks and their supervisors, with societies merely expressing support for
their regulator.
The Treasury did not address regulation in the consultation paper it
published for its review of societies' powers.
</TEXT>
