<HEADLINE>
FT  24 NOV 94 / Zeneca moves to individual pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Zeneca, the chemical and pharmaceutical company, has decided to end
collective bargaining with unions representing 8,200 white-collar staff in
its UK plants.
The company has given union officials six months' notice of its intention to
abandon company-wide negotiations on pay and conditions of service including
hours of work, holidays, working arrangements, shifts and security of
employment.
From next April, the pay of Zeneca's staff will be determined through
assessment by local management of individual performance, ending the old
system of annual across-the-board cost-of-living awards in addition to merit
review rises.
Zeneca's move has come as a shock to union leaders. Earlier this week they
met Mr David Barnes, the company's chief executive, to discuss the new
strategy.
They told him the overwhelming majority of white-collar staff in Zeneca was
opposed to the end of collective bargaining and urged him to test their
views by holding an independent survey.
In a statement to the staff, the five unions involved accused the company of
'blatant ideological opportunism'.
The statement said: 'It represents the reversal of every assurance given to
the unions and every statement made by the company . . . It has been done in
an underhand way and against all the principles of consultation which have
developed at national level over many years.' The company said less than 30
per cent of white-collar staff belonged to a trade union. Unions could still
represent their members in the company on disciplinary and grievance issues
as well as health and safety. 'We wish to continue to have an open dialogue
with the unions,' it said.
Zeneca said it had no intention of ending collective pay bargaining for
manual worker grades. 'We have no experience of operating a merit pay scheme
with them,' it said.
</TEXT>
