<HEADLINE>
FT  24 NOV 94 / Clarke may act over executive pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shareholders may be given increased powers to curb excessive pay increases
for top company executives, Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, disclosed in
the Commons yesterday.
He revealed that the practical issues involved were under examination as the
government came under renewed pressure to condemn the 75 per cent rise
awarded to Mr Cedric Brown, British Gas chief executive.
It is understood that the chancellor has had preliminary discussions with Mr
Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, about the legislative
implications of increasing shareholder power.
Mr Clarke ruled out renewed Labour demands for the imposition of a windfall
tax on the excess profits of the privatised utilities, and for executive
salaries to be brought within the regulatory regimes which oversee their
pricing policies.
He said he disapproved of large salary increases in any company which went
far beyond what could be deemed reasonable in relation to their performance.
The continuing chorus of disapproval about the rewards available to the
heads of the privatised utilities dominated the final stages of the six-day
debate on the Queen's Speech.
Sir Edward Heath updated the phrase he used when, as prime minister, he
condemned the activities of Lonrho, by describing Mr Brown's increase as the
'unacceptable post-privatisation face of capitalism'.
He added: 'Why do I condemn it? Because it shows he has absolutely no
understanding of public relations between his corporation and the public -
absolutely none.'
Mr Malcolm Bruce, Liberal Democrat Treasury spokesman, also opposed a
windfall tax - but called for excess profits to be returned to consumers
through rebates.
Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, said the profit levels of the
privatised utilities had increased by 50 per cent during the recession when
other companies had been forced to cut back. He said the people of Britain
were 'increasingly disgusted' by the excessive pay rises. Mr Brown also
called for action in next week's Budget to 'end short-termism' in relation
to dividends, but admitted that there was little prospect of the action
materialising.
Mr Clarke said he had been able to prepare the Budget against the background
of the 'most encouraging set of economic prospects' for many years.
The 'lasting recovery' that he intended to deliver would give real hope in
the future 'for prosperity and for jobs'.
</TEXT>
