FT  24 NOV 94 / Ulster's isolation compounded by lack of integration
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEWART DALBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The isolation of Ulster is compounded by its lack of integration with the
republic of Ireland, the institute says in its review, Stewart Dalby writes.
It sees hope in the peace process, saying that an end to the troubles could
help bring about an integration in the vital areas of manufacturing and
food.
The institute calls into question a perception that Ulster's fringe position
in the UK could be a deterrent to inward investment. The review says
transport costs from the province to places such as Berlin and Milan are
substantially lower than costs to the same places from Dublin. Costs to New
York are 27 per cent less.
