<HEADLINE>
FT  24 NOV 94 / Ministers fail to speed up the superhighway: Little is
changed by the government's latest statement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Even seasoned observers of the fast-changing telecommunications scene took
time to absorb the implications of the government's latest statement on the
development of the 'information superhighway', published earlier this week.
In 35 pages it reinforces the government's commitment to the multimedia
revolution but does little to alter the commercial playing field.
The statement is in part a formal response to the views of the parliamentary
committee on optical fibre networks which were published earlier this year.
The MPs argued that British Telecommunications should be free to offer
broadcast entertainment across its existing network - a conclusion which BT
wholeheartedly supports.
This week's government paper, Creating the Superhighways of the Future,
rejects that idea, but seems to offer BT and public telecommunications
operators the opportunity to test their broadcasting ambitions on a small
scale. But very little has changed.
BT wants to offer the broadest range of services across its network. The
government, anxious to stimulate competition in telecommunications and to
encourage investment by cable television companies, has denied it permission
to broadcast entertainment.
It is not, however, prevented from offering 'on-demand' services such as
movies, home shopping or home banking. An ambitious series of trials in the
south-east of England will test its ability to deliver these services.
Under the terms of the government's last telecommunications review in 1991,
there will be no revision of the ban on broadcast entertainment before 2001.
This week's paper underlined that commitment.
Cable companies, however, were empowered to offer telephone services as well
as entertainment over their networks under the terms of the 1991 review.
This assurance of phone revenues was critical in persuading cable companies
to make the heavy investments needed - a total of about Pounds 10bn by 2000
 -to construct an adequate cable infrastructure.
By the end of next year about 6.5m homes will be connected to cable and more
are being connected at a rate of between 1m and 2m a year.
The 1990 Broadcasting Act rewrote the licence for cable television
operators. The newly named Local Delivery Operators can deliver
entertainment using radio technology as well as cable to clearly defined
franchise areas such as a city or local authority area.
There are 127 existing franchises; a further nine have been advertised which
will be let under the new terms. A further 30 or so have yet to be defined
geographically. When that has been done, about 95 per cent of the country
will be covered.
This week's paper argues that BT and other telecommunications operators have
been able, since April, to apply for any advertised franchise. If they were
successful, the government would be prepared to grant a licence to supply
entertainment within the area of the franchise. They would be able to use
either their existing technology - in BT's case, the conventional telephone
lines into the home - or another, such as cable or radio.
In fact, this freedom has always been available to BT although it has rarely
sought to advertise the fact. Mr Richard Woollam, director of the Cable
Communications Association, the cable trade body, said yesterday: 'All the
government is saying to BT is 'Come and join the cable party'.'
BT has no intention of contributing to a piecemeal approach to the recabling
of Britain. It owned a number of cable franchises at one stage but sold
them. It has not overinvested in Westminster Cable, one franchise it
retained. It wants to spend Pounds 15bn to create its own network in
competition with the cable operators.
Nothing in the government's latest paper alters this stalemate.
</TEXT>
<XX>
