<HEADLINE>
FT  24 NOV 94 / Getting the dirt on mucky past: The latest moves in the
struggle to clean up contaminated land
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON LONDON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government's forthcoming legislation on contaminated land will be the
latest stage of a five-year struggle to get to grips with the legacy of
Britain's industrial past.
In 1990 the Commons environment committee published its first report on
contaminated land, estimating that up to 100,000 sites could be described as
contaminated.
The government was quick to respond - too quick, according to its critics.
Section 143 of the Environmental Protection Act, passed in November 1990,
proposed that district councils maintain publicly available registers of
contaminated sites.
The idea, in line with the environment committee's proposals, aimed to
assist local authorities and developers by identifying potential problems.
But the proposal soon ran into difficulties as the government consulted
local authorities and the property industry on what the register should
include.
It is costly to establish if a site is actually contaminated, so the
government proposed that inclusion should be based on the historic uses of
the land. The first consultation document suggested a list of 40 uses which
could potentially cause contamination.
Environmental groups applauded the proposals but landowners and property
developers argued that the net had been cast too widely.
There was clearly a risk that formerly industrialised areas would be
blighted as developers chose to build on greenfield sites instead.
The Merry Hill shopping centre, built on a former steelworks, was just one
site in the heavily industrialised Black Country which would have been
affected. The Department of the Environment's London headquarters, built on
the site of a gas works, would also have appeared on the register.
The number of uses that might cause contamination was later reduced to
eight, which would have cut the area covered by 90 per cent.
However there were other reasons why the proposals were seen as unworkable.
One problem was that contaminated land would have stayed on the proposed
register even after cleaning. The government's arguments for this were: that
information on the site's history would be necessary when any future change
of use was proposed; contamination from a site might have moved to adjacent
sites; treatment rarely removed all contamination, while new hazards might
be discovered later.
More seriously, the proposals did not address the problems of clean-up
targets and funding. Without targets or an idea of who should pay to meet
them the register would not have solved the underlying problem.
Mr Michael Howard, then environment secretary, announced in March last year
that Section 143 would not be brought into force. But that was by no means
the end of the problem. Numerous acts of parliament set out criminal and
financial penalties for contamination. Property owners had no way of knowing
the extent of potential liabilities.
The question of liability was clarified by the Lords ruling last December in
a battle between Cambridge Water and Eastern Counties Leather over liability
for water pollution.
The Lords ruled that Eastern Counties Leather, a leather treatment company,
could not be held responsible for pollution caused years ago because it
could not reasonably have foreseen the damage.
In doing so, they rejected the application of strict liability of the kind
which applies in the US - that polluters are liable regardless of whether
they foresaw the damage or took steps to alleviate it.
In March the government published a consultation paper, Paying For Our Past,
with preliminary conclusions about the direction of future legislation.
The paper included three principles:
US-style strict liability would not be introduced. In line with the
Cambridge Water ruling polluters should, in general, only be liable if they
were at fault and could have anti-cipated the problem.
Land need not be cleaned to a pristine state, only to the level necessary
for its intended use. The proposal, which has been attacked by
environmentalists, is an attempt to avoid some of the huge clean-up bills
which have arisen in other countries.
Although polluters should be primarily responsible for clean-up costs, banks
should, in some circumstances, be held liable for cleaning pollution caused
by companies to which they had made loans. This worried bankers, who argued
that it would discourage lending to industry.
 -----------------------------------------------------
                   MAN-MADE WASTELANDS
 -----------------------------------------------------
February 1990 - Environment select committee's
                first report on contaminated land
 -----------------------------------------------------
November 1990 - Environmental Protection Act.
                Section 143 proposes public
                registers of contaminated land
 -----------------------------------------------------
March 1993    - Government abandons section 143
                proposals
 -----------------------------------------------------
December 1993 - House of Lords rules on Cambridge
                Water case.  Polluter not liable
                retrospectively where damage could
                not have been foreseen
 -----------------------------------------------------
March 1994    - Paying For Our Past consultation
                document
 -----------------------------------------------------
</TEXT>
