<HEADLINE>
FT  24 NOV 94 / BBC to push ahead with digital television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The BBC has decided in principle to push ahead with the launch of digital
terrestrial television and a near-national service could begin as early as
the autumn of 1997.
A BBC study of the issue following the government white paper on the future
of the corporation has come to a positive interim conclusion.
Terrestrial digital television involves turning the conventional television
picture into digits, the language of computers, but broadcasting through
land-based transmitters rather than by satellite.
The technology would allow the launch of wide-screen television - giving a
picture shaped like a cinema screen - and a number of extra channels.
As many as 12 new digital television channels could be created in the UK and
broadcast alongside the conventional four national channels.
The BBC believes digital technology will win over existing analogue
technology in the end. A crossover period of 10 to 15 years is likely,
however, when the two systems will have to be broadcast at the same time so
that no one is deprived of their basic television service.
The BBC may carry out its first public technical trial in March and a
limited regional trial could get under way in 1995 or 1996.
The BBC, as a publicly funded organisation, can initiate the first steps in
creating a digital terrestrial service. Executives emphasise, however, that
nothing of substance will happen unless the project is supported by other
British broadcasters and by the consumer electronics companies which would
manufacture the set-top boxes and new television sets.
Mr Charles Allan, chief executive of both Granada Television and LWT,
recently expressed interest in digital terrestrial television and the
possibility of creating new channels that it offered.
The BBC has been having talks with consumer electronics companies such as
Sony and with representatives of the ITV system.
In its white paper on the corporation's new Royal Charter the government
appeared to link a BBC move into digital television with privatisation or
partial privatisation of its transmitter network. The assumption appeared to
be that some of the money raised could be used for funding the launch of
digital.
The BBC argues that keeping it intact will increase its ability to make the
investment and commitment needed for digital.
The hope in the BBC is that a digital terrestrial service might be launched
by 1997 covering up to 80 per cent of the UK, possibly with a private-sector
partner.
On Monday the BBC will announce it is going ahead with two 24-hour a day
satellite channels for Europe in a joint venture with Pearson, the media and
entertainment group that owns the Financial Times.
</TEXT>
