<HEADLINE>
FT  24 NOV 94 / Naval dockyards attract only one bidder each
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Labour party yesterday accused the government of botching another
proposed privatisation after the Ministry of Defence announced it had
received only two initial bids for the Royal dockyards at Rosyth in Fife and
Devonport in Plymouth.
Five months after the government announced it was putting the yards up for
sale, the ministry said that Devonport Management had been the only bidder
for the Devonport yard and Babcock International Group the only bidder for
Rosyth.
The companies have been managing the respective yards on behalf of the
government since 1987, but their contracts are set to expire shortly.
It is understood that a dozen other companies, including GEC and BAe, had
registered an interest in buying the Devonport yard earlier this year.
However, the MoD has asked companies bidding for the yards to carry the
heavy risks involved in fixed-price contracts and to give guarantees over
the cost of refits for at least the first five years after sale. In a
Commons written answer yesterday, Mr Roger Freeman, defence procurement
minister, said the government was evaluating the bids. He added: 'Outcomes
other than sale cannot be ruled out.'
His announcement came two weeks after the government abandoned plans to
privatise the Post Office, and drew a rebuke from Labour.
Dr David Clark, shadow defence secretary, said: 'This is yet another failed
government privatisation plan. It is now time the government stopped putting
ideology before practicality. You can't privatise Britain's security
requirements.'
Labour accused the government of spending more than Pounds 2m hiring City
consultants and bankers to advise on the privatisation, only to find an
absence of competition when the initial deadline for tenders had passed.
A range of management consultants and banks have advised the government on
the sale, including Coopers &amp; Lybrand and Kleinwort Benson. Under Treasury
guidelines, ministers are obliged to hire specialist consultants when
considering privatisation of state assets.
The MoD said last night that bids could still be received even though the
initial deadline had passed. It added: 'We will be going into negotiations
for the final bids shortly, but the government will only accept bids that
provide value for money for the taxpayer.'
</TEXT>
