<HEADLINE>
FT  24 NOV 94 / Outspoken Tory resigns party post
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Patrick Nicholls last night resigned as a Conservative party
vice-chairman after making an outspoken attack on the French and Germans in
his local newspaper.
The MP for Teignbridge and former minister said he bitterly regretted any
embarrassment he might have caused to the government in the article, which
was disowned by Conservative Central Office.
He said remarks about Germany and France had deflected from the main message
of the article which was that 'our destiny lies in Europe'.
He said his comments had also deflected attention from the fact that the
prime minister had been 'singularly successful in securing Britain's
interests in Europe'. That was why he would be supporting the government in
the vote on Monday on a bill increasing Britain's contributions to the
European Union budget.
Mr Nicholls quit as junior environment minister when caught drink-driving at
the 1990 Tory party conference. He had previously been at the employment
department where he was a member of the ministerial group on alcohol misuse.
Writing in the Western Morning News, Mr Nicholls ridiculed Germans as
warmongers and French as cowards. He said Germany's main contribution to
Europe had been to plunge the Continent into two world wars within living
memory. 'Too many of my compatriots have died to the strains of Deutschland
uber Alles,' he said.
Mr Nicholls dismissed the French as 'a nation of collaborators', who
presented themselves as a nation of resistance fighters. France was
'incapable of winning any war unless it is fought by the French Foreign
Legion, and only then because it is officered for the most part by English,
Americans and Germans'.
Mr Nicholls wrote: 'I wish I was not in the European Community. It is far
from the merely economic community we were led to expect, and if I thought
it was feasible to leave it, I would be off tomorrow.'
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, said he deplored 'a statement of rather
old-fashioned prejudices against anybody on the continent of Europe'. Mr
Nicholls' comments were not a helpful approach. 'One of the things I am
anxious to do is have an intelligent European debate.'
Mrs Noreen Atkinson, Mr Nicholls's constituency chairman, said she thought
he had been trying to put the case 'very squarely'.
Mr Nicholls, 46, is a former ministerial aide to Mr David Mellor in the Home
Office and Mr John Gummer in the Ministry of Agriculture. He fought off a
strong centre-party challenge to win his seat in 1983.
A strong loyalist with a reputation for forcefully defending government
policies, he was given special responsibilities for campaigning in May 1993
when he was appointed one of the five vice-chairmen who help run the party
organisation under Mr Jeremy Hanley, the Tory chairman.
</TEXT>
