<HEADLINE>
FT  24 NOV 94 / Conservatives divided over EU budget forecast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tory MPs were deeply split last night over an analysis of forecast UK
contributions to the European Union budget released by the Treasury.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, took the extraordinary step of releasing
figures from the Budget Red Book, expected on Tuesday, to provide a sound
statistical argument for a crucial parliamentary debate on Monday.
Mr Clarke said the figures proved 'incontrovertibly' that the increase in UK
contributions caused by the European communities finance bill would be
limited to Pounds 75m next year and Pounds 250m a year by 1999.
But Eurosceptic backbenchers seized on an admission that this year's net
contribution would be Pounds 720m higher than forecast, and said the
analysis justified claims that UK payments would rise by up to Pounds 1bn by
the end of the century.
Mr Edward Leigh, a rightwing former minister, said the analysis 'justifies
everything that we have been saying'. He added: 'We are not talking about
small amounts of money, we are talking about a serious issue of principle.'
Mr Clarke said he was 'quite confident' that the government would win the
second reading vote on the bill following the government's announcement that
it would call a general election in the event of a rebel victory.
The Treasury figures, released in a Commons written answer, update last
year's Red Book forecasts for net UK contributions from Pounds 1.7bn to
Pounds 2.4bn for the current year, an increase of Pounds 720m.
The figures also show that the forecast payment for next year has been
reduced by Pounds 64m to just under Pounds 3.4bn, and the forecast payment
for 1996-97 has fallen by Pounds 179m to Pounds 3.3bn.
Overall, Britain's net contributions are now forecast to be Pounds 963m
higher over the three years to 1996-97 than was expected, partly because of
the effect of faster UK growth on the complex formula that determines
payments.
However, none of the forecast rise is attributable to the provisions of the
bill, which implements a deal reached by Mr John Major, the prime minister,
and Mr Norman Lamont, then chancellor, at the Edinburgh EU summit in 1992.
In separate figures stripping out irregularities in payments caused by
technical factors, the Treasury forecasts that underlying net contributions
will rise from Pounds 2.5bn this year to Pounds 3.5bn in 1999.
It says that Pounds 600m of the Pounds 850m rise between next year - the
first affected by the bill - and 1999 is due to growth and inflation. Only
Pounds 250m is attributable to the Edinburgh deal.
</TEXT>
