FT  24 NOV 94 / BAe to shed 750 Airbus workers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Aerospace is to shed 750 jobs next year at its Airbus plants at
Filton, Bristol, and Broughton, near Chester.
Most of the losses will be at Filton, where 550 jobs will go with the
completion of a contract for the conversion of VC10 aircraft into RAF
refuelling tanker aircraft. BAe said the majority of jobs would be lost in
the first quarter of 1995, and would affect all categories of staff. It
hoped all redundancies would be voluntary.
The Airbus division employs 6,500 at the two plants and BAe has reduced the
workforce by 900 this year. In September, Raytheon, the US company which
bought the BAe executive jet division, announced it would close by 1997 an
adjacent factory in Broughton with the loss of 550 jobs.
Mr Chris Geoghegan, BAe Airbus managing director, said the reduction in
defence spending and pressure on civil programmes emphasised the importance
of the proposed European Future Large Aircraft. He urged the government to
consider it seriously rather than rushing to buy the Hercules C130J from
Lockheed as the RAF's transport aircraft
Nuclear Electric yesterday said 80 jobs were to be shed at Sizewell A power
station in Suffolk. The first 50 jobs will go over the next year. Staff are
being asked to take voluntary redundancy.
Yorkshire cuts jobs, Page 27
