FT  24 NOV 94 / Hopes for housing trusts dashed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBYN CHALMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr David Curry, the housing minister, yesterday poured cold water on hopes
that a class of investment trust to increase the supply of private rented
accommodation would be introduced in the Budget.
Interest groups including the Association of Residential Letting Agents, the
independent Housing Investment Group and the Joseph Rowntree Foundation had
hoped legislation would be changed to allow for authorised housing
investment trusts.
The proposed trusts were aimed at promoting institutional investment in the
private rented sector. They would be free from capital gains tax and pay
corporation tax at the lower rate of 25 per cent.
Mr Curry told a conference in London that no industry estimates had been
provided on levels of subsidy needed.
Once an estimate had been concluded, Mr Curry said, he would be prepared to
explore the option in line with the government's objective of encouraging
growth in the sector.
Mrs Patsy Baker, of the Housing Investment Group, said the organisation had
suggested that the government make Pounds 250m available to the trusts by
way of a grant.
She said the grant would bridge the yield gap of 1.5 per cent existing
between investor requirements and the returns available in the private
rented sector.
