FT  24 NOV 94 / Italian coalition partners call for crisis meeting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Key partners in Italy's right-wing coalition government last night called
for a crisis meeting to assess its chances of survival in the wake of the
decision by magistrates to investigate corruption allegations against Prime
Minister Silvio Berlusconi.
The move highlighted the division within the Berlusconi government pitting
the populist Northern League of Mr Umberto Bossi against its partners. It
raised fears whether the government would last long enough to ensure the
1995 budget passed its last and hardest phase in the senate.
Yesterday, concern over Italy's political instability forced the lira to
another historic low against the D-Mark, being quoted at L1,035 against the
German currency.
President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro urged the passing of the 1995 budget. This
came after he met the speakers of the two houses, Mr Carlo Scognamiglio and
Ms Irene Pivetti, two people likely to play a vital role in the coming days.
The statement pointed out the present government could be changed only by a
parliamentary vote of no confidence.
Tensions within the government have been heightened in the wake of Tuesday's
decision by Milan magistrates to place Mr Berlusconi under investigation for
alleged corruption while running his Fininvest business empire.
Mr Bossi said the government should only survive until the budget is
approved. But yesterday the League leader and other members of his party
were absent from a meeting of the coalition. This was attended by Mr Cesare
Previti, defence minister and chief co-ordinator of Mr Berlusconi's Forza
Italia movement, Mr Gianfranco Fini, leader of the neo-fascist MSI/National
Alliance, and Mr Pierfernando Casini, head of the small Christian Democrat
Centre.
Their call for an immediate clarification of where each coalition partner
stood appeared aimed at forcing Mr Bossi's hand as well as assessing
survival tactics. Mr Berlusconi yesterday stood by his claim of innocence.
But Milan magistrates indicated they had taken evidence against him from 16
sources. Today, talks are due between government and unions in an attempt to
head off the planned general strike on December 2 to protest at the budget
and plans to cut pensions.
Observer, Page 23
</TEXT>
