<HEADLINE>
FT  24 NOV 94 / Strike-hit Iberia turns to Plan B
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Iberia, Spain's financially crippled national carrier, faced a major
industrial dispute yesterday as its management announced after a board
meeting that it would shed 5,200 jobs from its 25,000 labour force and
drastically reduce the size of the airline.
Unions, which had rejected an earlier management plan to cut salaries by an
average 15 per cent, said they would blockade Spain's airports in protest at
the management's plans.
As the confrontation at Iberia began to look ominously like the violent
industrial dispute at Air France a year ago, the company's employees began
holding mass meetings at Madrid's Barajas airport and at other domestic
airports last night.
With tension running high, one union spokesman said: 'We are not preparing
strikes, we are getting together to plan the closedown of air traffic in
Spain.'
Mr Javier Salas, chairman of Iberia, and president of INI, the state holding
group that owns the airline, said the company would hive off some of its key
units under a series of emergency measures that Iberia's board has called
Plan B.
The proposed measures effectively mean that Iberia renounces its ambitions
to be a global carrier and scales down to become a regional airline.
Plan B involves the sale of Iberia's subsidiaries to INI for subsequent
disposal. Iberia would hive off its shareholdings in a string of airlines
including Aerolineas Argentinas, Chile's Ladeco, Venezuela's Viasa and the
domestic carriers Aviaco, Binter Canarias and Binter Mediterraneo.
The measures involve the segregation of the company's handling, maintenance,
information systems and marketing units and their eventual sale. Iberia,
after such a break-up, would consist of a reduced aircraft fleet and a staff
of around 5,000, mostly pilots and cabin crews.
Mr Salas said the survival of Iberia in its present form would only be
possible if the earlier viability plan, which involved pay cuts and the loss
of 2,000 jobs, was accepted by the unions. Unions have already staged two
24-hour stoppages this month that grounded 75 per cent of Iberia's flights
in protest at the pay cuts.
Economy minister Mr Solbes said yesterday that if the airline's management
failed to gain union consent to its original viability plan it would have
full government backing to take other measures because 'there is no other
alternative.'
Under the terms of the viability plan, Iberia would also have sought
authorisation for public subsidies totalling Pta130bn (Pounds 640m) from the
European Commission. This request however depended on union agreement to the
pay cuts. Under Plan B, the management shelves the recapitalisation plan and
will instead meet the urgent need for fresh funding by breaking up the
company and scaling down the airline to a fraction of its present size.
Iberia is expected to lose Pta44bn this year, up on earlier estimates of
Pta30bn, and its accumulated losses by December will have effectively wiped
out a Pta120bn capital injection that was authorised by Brussels in 1992. Mr
Salas has said there is a 'serious risk' that the company could be 'legally
bankrupt and forced into liquidation' early next year.
</TEXT>
