<HEADLINE>
FT  23 NOV 94 / Lilley rejects call over pensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Peter Lilley, the social security secretary, last night rejected demands
that the new private pensions regulator should be financed by the taxpayer.
He insisted it was 'proper' that the cost should be met by occupational
pension schemes.
He emphasised that not all taxpayers benefited from such schemes and did not
see why they should meet the cost.
In the first vote of the new parliamentary session the government defeated
Labour calls for regulations to control the mis-selling of private pensions
and for the abandonment of the jobseekers allowance by a majority of 37
(309-272).
Mr Donald Dewar, shadow social security secretary, underlined the need to
ensure that the new regulator was seen to be independent. He warned: 'He
will not have that independence if the industry is seen as his paymaster.'
Mr Lilley looked to the encouragement of increased self-provision of
pensions and the reinforced incentive to work provided by the jobseekers
allowance to limit the cost of social security provision.
Earlier, Mrs Virginia Bottomley, the health secretary, brushed aside
suggestions that policy decisions on limiting tobacco advertising had been
influenced by lobbying organisations. She was challenged about a report in
The Guardian newspaper referring to a meeting between Mr Keith Mans, her
parliamentary private secretary, and the Outdoor Advertising Action Group.
Mrs Bottomley said Mr Mans, who is Conservative MP for Wyre, had no
recollection of such a meeting. She insisted no holder of her office would
be able to do the job unless used to 'energetic lobbying' from people
concerned with particular policies.
The six-day debate on the Queen's Speech ends today.
</TEXT>
