<HEADLINE>
FT  23 NOV 94 / Call for change in societies' rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Nationwide Building Society, the country's second biggest, yesterday called
for a single qualifying period before society members become eligible for
rights and benefits of membership.
Mr Brian Davis, Nationwide chief executive, said in giving evidence to the
Commons Treasury committee inquiry into financial regulation that there was
a case for a single statutory test of membership - having been an investor
or a borrower for a set period of time such as two years - which would apply
for voting and ownership.
While such a change would reduce the number of members eligible to vote,
when there was increased emphasis on societies' accountability, it would
remove some of the anomalies of the current arrangements.
In the case of the Lloyds Bank bid for Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester Building
Society only C&amp;G investing members of more than two years' standing could
receive a cash share of the price, although a larger number of members -
including borrowers - could vote on whether to accept the offer.
The society's written submission to the committee called for a single
regulatory framework for financial services with just one watchdog covering
areas now handled by a range of bodies including the Building Societies
Commission and the Securities and Investments Board, the chief City
regulator.
MPs on the cross-party committee pressed Mr Davis about why Nationwide had
entered a 'tied' relationship to sell the financial services products of
Guardian Royal Exchange, the insurer, instead of offering independent
financial advice.
He said the link provided a chance to work closely with the supplier and
improve administration in order to reduce costs.
</TEXT>
