<HEADLINE>
FT  23 NOV 94 / World Trade News: 'Progress' in congressional talks on Gatt
deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Bill Clinton said yesterday progress had been made in negotiations
with Senator Robert Dole, the Republican Senate leader, whose support is
vital to passage of the Uruguay Round trade deal in the US Congress.
Clearly hoping for bipartisan amity on trade, at the very least, Mr Clinton
praised Senator Dole's 'constructive approach' on 'substantive issues
surrounding the Gatt.' However, he rejected the senator's attempt at the
weekend to link passage of the Round package with a cut in the capital gains
tax.
Mr Mickey Kantor, US trade representative, has been in constant contact with
Senator Dole, who must appease his party's right wing which professes to
fear an encroachment by the proposed World Trade Organisation on US
sovereignty.
Senator Dole has reportedly proposed a panel of retired federal judges who
would review decisions by the WTO dispute settlement panels. If the panels
rule against the US improperly three times, within a certain period of time,
then Congress could vote to withdraw from the WTO.
Time for a deal is running short. The House is due to vote next Tuesday, and
the Senate three days later. The four-day Thanksgiving holiday intervenes,
starting tomorrow. This leaves little time to build momentum in favour of
the Round. Lobbyists say once Senator Dole signs on to a deal, the political
dynamic changes. Unwilling to be seen as a leader who cannot deliver, he
will work hard to bring fellow Republicans with him.
In the House, where the legislation has been expected to pass easily, many
members have become edgy about casting a controversial vote when the
legislation may not make it to the Senate floor. A number of Republicans who
want the Uruguay Round out of the way for their own agenda next year have
opposed its linkage with the capital gains tax cut.
'Dole wants to demonstrate that he is not insensitive to the concerns of the
conservatives,' said one former senior trade official. 'At the end of the
day he will not want to be seen as the one who brought Gatt down.' Questions
that opponents have raised about the WTO impinging on US sovereignty have
already been answered with some safeguards. The deal reached in Geneva would
allow any country to withdraw from the WTO after six months' notice.
</TEXT>
