<HEADLINE>
FT  23 NOV 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow plunges 91 points on rate
fears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA BRANSTEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US share prices plummeted late yesterday afternoon to finish at their lowest
since early July amid fears that further interest rate increases would begin
to slow economic growth, writes Lisa Bransten in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average blue chip indicator was down
91.52 at 3,677.99. The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 dropped 8.21
to 450.09, while the American Stock Exchange composite surrendered 5.14 at
436.14 and the Nasdaq composite tumbled 16.53 to 741.21. Trading volume on
the New York SE amounted to 385m shares.
Yesterday was the worst day for the Dow since February 4, the day the
Federal Reserve embarked on the current course of monetary tightening that
has driven interest rates from 3 per cent in January to today's 5.5 per
cent. On that day the Dow plunged more than 96 points.
The decline adds to Monday's loss of nearly 46 points, which took the Dow
down to its lowest level since August 22. NYSE volume yesterday was the
highest day's total of the year in the wake of investor fears that rising
interest rates would draw money from equities and into interest-bearing
instruments such as bonds.
On Monday, Morgan Stanley reduced the stock portion of its equity model
portfolio to 85 from 97 per cent and increased the cash holdings to 15 per
cent from 3 per cent.
For one of the first times this year, equity prices did not follow the trend
in bonds, which posted gains after an afternoon auction showed moderately
strong demand for five-year notes. Some analysts believe the uncoupling may
be a signal that the markets finally believe that the Fed is willing to
continue lifting interest rates until the economy slows down. Until now,
said some, many market actors were not convinced that the Fed was willing to
sacrifice some growth in order to rein in inflation.
Major cyclicals were off sharply. Caterpillar fell Dollars 3 1/4 to Dollars
51 5/8 , DuPont Dollars 2 to Dollars 52 3/4 , International Paper Dollars 2
7/8 to Dollars 68 1/8 , General Electric Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 46 1/2 ,
Minnesota Mining &amp; Manufacturing Dollars 2 to Dollars 50 5/8 and United
Technologies Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 55 7/8 .
One gainer in the Dow was Walt Disney, which rose Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 43
after reporting fourth-quarter earnings of 42 cents per share, against
analysts' expectations of 39 cents.
PaineWebber shed Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 13 after the SEC launched an
investigation into whether the broking house had improperly sold shares in
several limited partnerships to investors.
Greyhound Lines was unchanged at Dollars 2 after reporting that it would
take a net loss of Dollars 3.5m over about four years because of three
cancelled interest rate swaps.
Canada
Toronto stocks posted only moderate losses in spite of the carnage in New
York which was seen late in the Wall Street session amid active program
selling.
The TSE 300 index ended 16.16 lower at 4,058.15, while falls led rises by
557 to 240 after volume of 68.7m shares.
Ten of the 14 sub-group indices were down, led by transportation, metals,
industrial products and gold stocks. The golds group shed a further 0.7 per
cent, failing to benefit from a 70-cent gain in the New York spot bullion
price to USDollars 388.25 an ounce.
</TEXT>
