<HEADLINE>
FT  23 NOV 94 / The Lex Column: Cookson/JM
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Merger talks between Cookson and Johnson Matthey may have broken down
because the two sides could not agree on valuation. But the failure would
seem to confirm that there was little industrial logic in a combination. Had
there been, it would have been easier for one or other to give a little
ground on valuation. Instead, talks became bogged down as each side fought
for slightly greater shares of the merged company than implied by their
respective market capitalisations. The main driving forces behind the merger
talks were the ambitions of Mr Richard Oster, Cookson's chief executive, and
Mr David Davies, JM's chairman, to run larger companies. Just because this
deal has failed, those ambitions are unlikely to have faded.
</TEXT>
