<HEADLINE>
FT  23 NOV 94 / Government offers telecoms groups wider superhighway role
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE and RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government has challenged British Telecommunications and the UK's
growing band of public telecoms operators to play a full part in developing
the country's information superhighway.
In a Command Paper* published yesterday, it urged the operators to gain
experience by applying for local franchises to deliver a full range of
services, including broadcast entertainment, to homes within the franchise
area.
The paper confirmed, however, that the government does not plan to let BT
broadcast entertainment to homes nationally before 2001 at the earliest.
The issue is bitterly contested by BT, which has been banned from offering
broadcast entertainment over its network so that cable television can
establish itself. Cable television companies are, however, not barred from
offering telecoms services.
The Independent Television Commission, regulatory body for commercial
television, has advertised nine new local delivery licences - as cable
franchises are called - the latest in the past few days.
They are for four separate franchises in the Midlands, covering 248,000
homes.
The commission emphasised yesterday that BT could have applied for cable
television franchises like any other company.
BT said that the government decision meant 'the great leap in broadband
communication we were hoping to provide has been postponed for several
years'.
It is clear that BT does not intend to apply for large cable franchises,
such as that currently on offer which covers Northern Ireland. Instead it
wants the freedom to spend Pounds 15bn to create its own modern network to
compete against the cable companies.
Mr Ian Taylor, trade and technology minister, said he had appointed a group
of senior industrialists to advise him on multimedia and the information
superhighway.
They includes Mr Don Cruickshank, director-general of Oftel, the industry
watchdog, and Mr Peter Job, chief executive of Reuters. BT is permitted to
offer services including video-on-demand and home shopping over its national
network, contrary to an FT report earlier this week. Creating the
Superhighways of the Future: Developing Broadband Communications in the UK.
