<HEADLINE>
FT  23 NOV 94 / Leading Article: Opec dangers
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Organisation of Petroleum Exporting Countries yesterday took the
unprecedented step of extending its production ceiling for a year in an
attempt to coax oil prices upwards. The move, urged on the cartel by Saudi
Arabia, its largest and most influential producer, suggests Opec's capacity
to influence the direction and stability of oil prices survives.
Whether prices rise in the next six months, as Opec hopes, depends partly on
whether the production ceiling holds, partly on what happens to the output
of non-OPEC suppliers and partly on whether world demand rises.
Unfortunately for Opec, the weather in many northern countries has been warm
so far this autumn. Nonetheless, the expansion in demand from rapidly
growing non-OECD countries is now large enough to compensate for recessions
in industrialised countries, in sharp contrast to the pattern in 1973 and
1982. As a result, world demand for oil, which hovered between 55m and 65m
barrels per day between 1973 and 1990, has broken out of that range to some
68m b/d this year.
On the evidence of this week's meeting, Opec should be able to deliver the
broadly predictable oil prices oil-importing countries desire, particularly
if the cartel continues to operate against the more comfortable background
of steadily rising world demand.
Over time, Opec's share of the world's production is also likely to creep
upwards, at least so long as investment in production outside Opec remains
restrained by moderate price levels.
But the result is also likely to be a growing concentration of output inside
Opec, since only Saudi Arabia looks capable of supplying much of any
longer-term increase in demand.
The markets have been more pre-occupied with the possibility that Iraq will,
at some point, resume exporting oil, once it has complied with enough of the
conditions imposed by the United Nations after the Gulf war. But its return
would probably add only about 1m b/d to world production, a third of its
pre-war levels.
The question about Iraq obscures the far greater importance of Saudi Arabia,
which accounts for a third of Opec production and a seventh of the whole
world's.
Provided that it has adequate resources to invest in more production, which
it should, even in its current cash-strapped state, it is well placed to
increase its share of Opec's output as world demand grows.
Saudi Arabia's ability to adjust its production to demand, in both
directions, can secure the price stability so much desired by the rest of
the world. It would do no harm if that stability were to be about a gently
rising trend. For the moment at least, the kingdom also feels it has a
strong interest in providing what is needed. The problem, however, is that
the stability of the world's oil market and so of the global economy is
correspondingly vulnerable to any Saudi political turmoil, or radical change
in objectives.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QNZ  Organisation of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P1311 Crude Petroleum and Natural Gas.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
    MKTS  Production.
</TP>
